Not for large libraries or video game music enthusiasts.  This app is best for small music collections full of singles instead of many large albums of multiple discs.  Using AirSync on a Mac to a Samsung Galaxy Prime J7.  Sync is slow and my phone frequently does not appear in the Mac app unless I kill doubleTwist on the phone, restart it, and then Scan for Devices on the desktop app.  Often I will need to reboot my phone to get it to appear in the desktop app.  Major changes to your iTunes library are not reflected in the desktop app or sent to the sync target.  For example, I exited the AirSync app on my Mac.  Then I started iTunes and edited the Album Artist and Track Artist for all tracks on an album.  Then I quit iTunes and verified these changes were in the Library XML file.  The metadata on these tracks were  not updated when I next opened AirSync on the Mac and thus weren't synced to my phone.  The sync does not work if you have multiple tracks with the same name on an album, even if they're on different discs for the same album.  I have the 'All Sounds of Final Fantasy I+II' album on my phone that contains the soundtrack to both games.  This album contains two discs.  iTunes has no problem putting both of these discs under the same album even if several tracks share the same name.  AirSync can't handle this - it will upload one of the two and leave the other missing.  This is because it stores the track names without track numbers - example: the third song on the second disc of an album named "Example" is stored by iTunes as "02-03 Example", but AirSync stores it as "Example.mp3".  So if the fifth song on a the third disc of the same album is also named "Example" then iTunes stores it as "03-05 Example.mp3" while AirSync overwrites "Example.mp3".
I'd like my money back!   It might work 1 out of 10 times.  What happened?  DoubleTwist used to be really good.

content: In theory, this should be a great app. In practice, it forces your screen to be awake during the entire music syncing process, and the transfer speed (even on a 55M+ Mbps WiFi connection) is abysmal. So to the doubleTwist developer: if iSyncr is capable of a transfer speed that's at least 2-3x faster than yours and doesn't require the display to be enabled during sync (allowing it as an option, but not a requirement)... why can't you get AirSync figured out? Admittedly your apps are a whole lot prettier looking, but this isn't nearly enough. I've tried numerous times over the past several years to switch from iSyncr to doubleTwist based solely on the fact that doubleTwist has a nice UI (although you advertise it as a Material UI, which is absolutely is not), but every single time I regret it and switch back immediately. Please take this as an important bit of feedback.

I got the AirSync for the convenience of wireless syncing, but whenever I use this app I have to constantly take my phone out of my pocket to keep it from toasting, and plug it in to charge.  The screen turns and stays *on* whenever synchronization occurs (even on devices that support wifi connections while the screen is disabled). So the battery drains and the device heats quickly while syncing. Also, the app's custom lockscreen isn't hard to accidentally unlock.   There aren't any real settings/options in the app (unless you count utilities to enable/disable  AirSync, pair with a computer, or reset the passcode.). Since you can't decrease the frequency of syncing or only sync while  charging, there's no real way to fix the above problem (where the screen turns/stays on and the battery drains). (The closest I've come to an automated fix is disabling the app via Tasker whenever my device is not charging.)   On the bright side, the app works in general: songs are synchronized from iTunes without a hitch (though this takes a while). Also, the developers have been responsive to my comments, and I'll update my review if/when the app improves. For now, though, it's not usable.

The new version now directly connects to iTunes, which allows to sync dynamic playlists as well. I use smart playlists quite a lot, therefore this change is highly welcome. There is one flaw left: If your changes on the phone (e.g. rating) change the smart playlist, AirSync does not allow iTunes to refresh before syncing again. Syncing music with an Android phone is harder than with an iPhone - this is perhaps the only edge Apple still has. This review is of the Doubletwist app but it applies to Airsync as well. First know that Doubletwist wired syncing currently doesn't work with the Galaxy S3. Second, Doubletwist promises to sync your iTunes library which it does, but this isn't the entire story. I found that I had random duplicate songs synced to my phone. These were my backups of certain purchased songs that were in subfolders. So while Doubletwist searches the selected folder for your iTunes playlist it appears to then search subfolders for other files. This would be ok if you were told about it. Third, my initial sync with Doubletwist included multiple failures - it was trying to sync songs I had deleted from my device a while ago. I had to delete some app data files, uninstall, reinstall, etc. I don't have a complicating hierarchy of files. This appears to be a common issue and it shouldn't be. Last, I've found that syncing doesn't delete songs from your phone - it will only add them. This is bad for keeping things organized and isn't really "syncing". App needs more focus.

content: There are a number of things wrong & annoying about this.  Firstly, in order to sync, it needs to switch the screen on.  Sometimes it shows the lock screen for a few seconds then fades out, but if you've been using your phone it can leave the screen on permanently.  Mine was on for several hours earlier before I noticed.  According to the support forum, this can be a problem for an initial sync and the official support response is to use the USB cable (even though you have just paid for the privilege to not have to do that!).  Oh and to top matters off, doubleTwist does not work with USB for a Galaxy S3 so you're stuck with your screen having a mind of it's own until completed.  Podcast support is woeful.  It doesn't integrate with a podcast library managed in iTunes, it just copies them as MP3s onto your device.  It doesn't update the played status so iTunes does not know to delete podcasts you've listened to.  If you then decide to use doubleTwist for podcast management, you get prompted to stump up another £5 when you first subscribe to a feed.  Frankly for £5, I was expecting something really polished, and this ain't even close to being even functional for me.  Ripoff.
